From 89a352957cfae9f1f4626a01c8879c91ae497139 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Yi-Wei Wang <yiweiw@nvidia.com>
Date: Wed, 17 Jul 2024 17:20:30 +0800
Subject: [PATCH 68/95] NVIDIA: SAUCE: pwm: tegra: Correct tegra_pwm_config()

tegra_pwm_config() should be responsible for calculating the pulse width
and frequency divider that will be written to the PWM control status
register. However, frequency divider was not properly utilized to
achieve the desired PWM output frequency due to the PWM source clock
manipulation.

The issue of existing PWM source clock manipulation can be explained by
below example. Assumed that the user specifies X nanoseconds as PWM
period in the device tree, aiming to produce PWM signal at (10^9 / X)Hz.
To achieve (10^9 / X)Hz PWM output frequency, PWM source clock should be
running at (10^9 / X * Y)Hz (Y is the resolution that PWM controller
can provide), which is the value assigned to required_clk_rate after
DIV_ROUND_UP_ULL() operation.

But it's not guaranteed that the PWM source clock can have the exact
same frequency step running at (10^9 / X * Y), which may be later
rounded down to the nearest frequency, say, 10^9 / X * Y - A by
clk_round_rate(pc->clk, required_clk_rate), causing the condition check
for (required_clk_rate > clk_round_rate(pc->clk, required_clk_rate))
being ture. Hence, the required_clk_rate is doubled which becomes
2 * (10^9 / X * Y). The 2 * (10^9 / X * Y) may be rounded down again by
clk_round_rate() in dev_pm_opp_set_rate(pc->dev, required_clk_rate),
say, 2 * (10^9 / X * Y) - B. The later mul_u64_u64_div_u64() will assign
(2 * (10^9 / X * Y) - B) * X / (10^9 * Y) which is equivalent to
2 - (B * X) / Y / 10^9 to `rate` that will be programmed to the
frequency divider field of the Tegra PWM controller. As the B, X, and Y
are always non negative, the value assigned to `rate` is always less
than or equal to 2, meaning the frequency divider cannot be properly
utilized.

This change eliminates manipulation of the PWM source clock by assigning
DIV_ROUND_CLOSEST_ULL(pc->clk_rate, required_clk_rate) - 1 to the
frequency divider.

Besides, the condition check of (pc->soc->num_channels == 1) is not
required since the PWM source clock manipulation is replaced with the
frequency divider which is supported on all generations of Tegra PWM
controllers.

It's also observed that the duty_width of early chips was defined as 8,
which is inaccurate since bit[24] of the pulse width field can be set to
1 to achieve 100% duty cycle. Therefore, this change updates duty_width
and clarifies the PWM controller's register layout in the comment
accordingly.

http://nvbugs/4748816

